Script 2: Populating the Artist Page

JavaScript

// Get the artist ID from the URL
const urlParams = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
const artistId = urlParams.get('id');

fetch('../data/artists.json')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(artists => {
    const artistContainer = document.querySelector('#populate-artist');
    const artist = artists.find(item => item.artistID === artistId);

    if (artist) {
      artistContainer.innerHTML = `
        <h3>${artist.artistName}</h3>
        <img src="${artist.artistImage}" alt="${artist.artistName}">
        <p>${artist.artistYear}</p>
        <p>${artist.pronouns}</p>
        <p>${artist.bio}</p>
      `;

      // Fetch the productions for this artist
      fetch('../data/productions.json')
        .then(response => response.json())
        .then(productions => {
          const artistProductions = productions.filter(item => item.artistID === artistId);
          const productionList = artistProductions.map(prod => `<li><a href="production.html?id=${prod.artistID}">${prod.projectName}</a></li>`).join('');
          artistContainer.innerHTML += `
            <h4>Related Projects</h4>
            <ul>${productionList}</ul>
          `;
        });
    }
  });
C贸digo generado por IA. Revisar y usar cuidadosamente. M谩s informaci贸n sobre preguntas frecuentes.
In these scripts, Im using the URLSearchParams object to get the ID from the URL. When you link to a production or artist page, you would include the ID in the URL like this: production.html?id=0 or artist.html?id=0. The script then uses this ID to fetch and display the correct data. This way, you can use the same script for each production or artist page, and it will automatically display the correct data based on the ID in the URL. I hope this helps! 

