la web
To set up URLs with parameters on GitHub Pages, you can follow these steps:

Create HTML files: For each page you want to create (for example, artist.html and production.html), create a corresponding HTML file in your GitHub repository.
Link to the pages: In your other HTML files, you can create links to these pages and include the ID parameter in the URL. Heres an example of how you can create such a link in HTML:
HTML

<a href="artist.html?id=0">Artist 0</a>
C贸digo generado por IA. Revisar y usar cuidadosamente. M谩s informaci贸n sobre preguntas frecuentes.
In this example, artist.html is the page youre linking to, and id=0 is the URL parameter youre passing to the page. When someone clicks this link, theyll be taken to the artist.html page, and the script on that page can access the id parameter from the URL.

Access URL parameters in JavaScript: In your JavaScript code, you can use the URLSearchParams object to access the URL parameters, as shown in the scripts I provided in the previous message.
Commit and push your changes: Once youve made these changes, commit and push them to your GitHub repository. GitHub Pages will automatically update to reflect your changes.
Test your pages: You can now navigate to your GitHub Pages site and test your new pages. Click the links you created to navigate to the new pages, and you should see the correct data displayed based on the ID in the URL.
Remember, when working with GitHub Pages, all your HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files need to be in the same repository, and you need to push your changes to the gh-pages branch if you have one, or to the main or master branch if you dont have a gh-pages branch. I hope this helps! 